```graph
digraph G {
    rankdir=LR;
    node [shape=box];

    Potentiometer -> Buffer -> LowPassFilter -> GainStage -> AntiAliasingFilter -> DAQ;

    subgraph cluster_0 {
        style=filled;
        color=lightgrey;
        node [style=filled,color=white];
        label = "Signal Conditioning";

        Buffer -> LowPassFilter -> GainStage -> AntiAliasingFilter;
    }
}
```

```Explanations
1. Potentiometer: Acts as a variable resistor, converting the angular position of the pendulum into a corresponding voltage signal. Its resistance changes linearly with the angle of the pendulum.

2. Buffer: Provides impedance matching between the potentiometer and subsequent stages. It ensures that the potentiometer’s output voltage does not drop significantly when connected to the next stage due to input impedance. A unity-gain buffer (voltage follower) is typically used here.

3. Low-Pass Filter: Attenuates unwanted high-frequency noise, including 50 and 60 Hz from electrical sources. This is important to ensure the signal representing the pendulum's angle is as clean as possible before amplification and digitization.

4. Gain Stage: Amplifies the signal to match the input range of the DAQ system. This block will scale the voltage from the potentiometer to fit within the +/- 7V range of the DAQ. The gain must be carefully set to avoid clipping while using the full dynamic range of the DAQ.

5. Anti-Aliasing Filter: A low-pass filter placed before the DAQ to remove frequencies higher than the Nyquist frequency, thus preventing aliasing when the analog signal is converted to digital. This filter should have a cutoff frequency just below half of the DAQ's sampling rate.

6. DAQ (Data Acquisition System): The final block in the signal path. It samples the conditioned analog signal and converts it to a digital format for further processing or display. It is not part of the signal conditioning but is the endpoint of the signal path in this context.
```

